  "title": "CRITICAL THERMAL MAXIMA IN TURTLES",
  "abstract": "The term critical maximum (CTM ) introduced by Cowles and Bogert (1944) is now well established in literature. The CTM was originally defined as the point at which locomotory activity becomes disorganized and animal loses its ability to escape from conditions that will promptly lead to its death. This definition was modified by Lowe and Vance (1955) to include statistical variation within samples, and by Hutchison (1961) to include certain criteria for heating rates. The CTM has been determined for a fairly large number of amphibians and reptiles by numerous authors, but there are few values available for turtles. Baldwin (1925) found that raising body temperature of painted turtles, Chrysemys picta, to 39-410C. for 30 minutes was fatal, but his methods and end point do not meet criteria for a CTM. The only values of CTM in literature appear to be those of Brattstrom (1961, 1965) for Pseudemys scripta, Chrysemys picta, Gopherus agassizi, and Trionyx ferox, and that of Cherchi (1956) for Testudo, hermanni. Brattstrom (1965, p. 377) stated that thermal maxima were usually determined in laboratory on acclimated animals, but acclimation temperatures were not given. Since few valid measurements of CTM of turtles have been made, we present this preliminary survey of 38 samples representing 25 species from a variety of habitats in hopes that it will add to knowledge of requirements of reptiles and thus lead to a better understanding of their ecology. This study was made possible by kindness of following persons who supplied most of live animals: Bernard S. Martof, John R. Freeman, J. S. Bleakney, James A. Fowler, Hayne L. Lindsey, Jr., Albert P. Blair, Robert L. Humphries, John. M. Legler, and Glenn Gentry; and by grants-in-aid from Sigma Xi and University of Rhode Island Research Committee.",
